<div class="docs-content__header">
  <span class="docs-content__eyebrow">Guides</span>
  <h1 class="docs-content__title">Budgets &amp; Governance</h1>
  <p class="docs-content__description">Control agent spending with per-column budgets, insert manual review steps, and track every change with audit logs.</p>
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <h2 id="budget-basics">Budget Basics</h2>
  <p>Every agent-driven column in Master of Puppets can have a <strong>monthly budget</strong> that caps how much it can spend on AI executions. Budgets are defined in cents and tracked against run costs within the current billing period. When a column exhausts its budget, Master of Puppets blocks further runs until the next period begins.</p>

  <h2 id="setting-a-budget">Setting a Budget</h2>
  <p>Set a column's budget on its edit page. The <strong>budget amount</strong> is the maximum monthly spend in dollars (stored as cents internally to avoid rounding errors). Manual columns don't have budgets &mdash; they don't run anything that costs money.</p>
  <p>Leave the budget at zero for unlimited spending. This is fine for development but should be configured for production operations.</p>

  <h2 id="spend-tracking">Spend Tracking</h2>
  <p>Master of Puppets tracks spending by summing the <code>cost_cents</code> of all <strong>runs</strong> a column produced within the current calendar month. Each time an adapter finishes, the run cost is recorded and counts toward the column's monthly spend.</p>
  <p>You can view budget utilization on the column's detail page: current spend, remaining budget, and utilization as a percentage.</p>

  <h2 id="alerts-and-enforcement">Alerts &amp; Enforcement</h2>
  <p>Master of Puppets provides two levels of budget control:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Alert threshold</strong> &mdash; when a column reaches 80% utilization, it triggers a warning. This gives you time to adjust before the budget is exhausted.</li>
    <li><strong>Hard enforcement</strong> &mdash; when the budget is fully exhausted, Master of Puppets refuses to start a new run on the column. The check happens <em>before</em> execution, so no resources are consumed on a blocked run.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Budget exhaustion is surfaced in error messages and run records so you can see exactly why an execution was blocked.</p>

  <h2 id="review-columns">Review Columns</h2>
  <p>Master of Puppets does not have per-action approval gates. Instead, governance is shaped by the board itself: insert a <strong>manual review column</strong> (transition policy <code>manual</code>, kind <code>review</code>) anywhere a human should sign off before work continues.</p>
  <p>When a task lands in a review column, no adapter runs &mdash; the task waits for a human to <em>advance</em> it (forward) or <em>reject</em> it (back to a previous column with feedback). Use review columns wherever a piece of work is high-stakes, customer-visible, or expensive to undo.</p>

  <h2 id="config-versioning">Config Versioning</h2>
  <p>Master of Puppets automatically versions changes to governance-sensitive column attributes. Every time you modify a column's name, transition policy, job spec, success criteria, adapter config, budget, or position, Master of Puppets creates a <strong>config version</strong> snapshot.</p>
  <p>Each version records:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>The <strong>action</strong> &mdash; create, update, or rollback</li>
    <li>The <strong>full snapshot</strong> &mdash; the complete state of the column at that point</li>
    <li>The <strong>changeset</strong> &mdash; only the fields that changed</li>
    <li>The <strong>author</strong> &mdash; who made the change (human user or agent)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>You can <strong>rollback</strong> to any previous version, restoring the column to that exact state. This provides a safety net when experimenting with column configurations.</p>

  <h2 id="audit-trail">Audit Trail</h2>
  <p>All changes to auditable resources (columns, tasks, documents, skills) are recorded as <strong>audit events</strong>, along with every column transition (advance, reject, block, manual_move, cancel). The audit trail captures who did what, when, and to which resource &mdash; whether the actor was a human user or a column run.</p>
  <p>Audit events are project-scoped and include metadata about the change. Use the audit trail to investigate unexpected agent behavior, track operational history, and maintain accountability.</p>
